# Web Page Testing Methodology

## Overview

Use the **cursor-browser-extension** MCP server to perform automated Chrome browser testing of web applications. This provides comprehensive UI testing beyond simple API endpoint checks.

## MCP Browser Tools Available

The browser automation tools are located in:
`C:\Users\FKGEISTA\.cursor\projects\c-opt-src-GenericLogHandler\mcps\cursor-browser-extension\tools\`

### Core Tools

| Tool | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `browser_navigate` | Navigate to a URL |
| `browser_click` | Click elements by ref ID |
| `browser_fill_form` | Fill form inputs |
| `browser_type` | Type text into focused element |
| `browser_wait_for` | Wait for time or element |
| `browser_snapshot` | Get current page state |
| `browser_take_screenshot` | Capture visual screenshot |
| `browser_console_messages` | Check for JS errors |
| `browser_evaluate` | Execute JavaScript |
| `browser_select_option` | Select dropdown options |

## Testing Workflow

### 1. Navigate to Page

```json
{
  "server": "cursor-browser-extension",
  "toolName": "browser_navigate",
  "arguments": {"url": "http://localhost:5000/"}
}
```

The response includes a **Page Snapshot** in YAML format showing:
- Page URL and Title
- Element tree with `ref` IDs for interaction
- Element states (active, checked, disabled, etc.)

### 2. Interact with Elements

Use the `ref` attribute from the snapshot to target elements:

```json
{
  "server": "cursor-browser-extension",
  "toolName": "browser_click",
  "arguments": {"element": "Refresh button", "ref": "e21"}
}
```

### 3. Wait for Dynamic Content

```json
{
  "server": "cursor-browser-extension",
  "toolName": "browser_wait_for",
  "arguments": {"time": 2000}
}
```

### 4. Verify Results

After interactions, the tool returns an updated snapshot showing:
- Changed element states
- New content loaded
- Updated text values

### 5. Check for JavaScript Errors

```json
{
  "server": "cursor-browser-extension",
  "toolName": "browser_console_messages",
  "arguments": {}
}
```

### 6. Capture Screenshots

```json
{
  "server": "cursor-browser-extension",
  "toolName": "browser_take_screenshot",
  "arguments": {"filename": "test-result.png"}
}
```

## Test Categories

### Page Load Tests
- Verify page loads without errors
- Check page title is correct
- Confirm essential elements are present

### Interactive Tests
- Click buttons and verify state changes
- Fill forms and submit
- Test navigation between pages
- Verify modals open/close
- Test dropdown selections

### Data Verification
- Confirm API data displays correctly
- Check tables populate with expected rows
- Verify counters and statistics update

### Visual Tests
- Take screenshots for visual comparison
- Verify charts render (Chart.js, etc.)
- Check theme toggle works

## Example Test Sequence

```
1. Navigate to http://localhost:5000/
2. Verify page title is "Generic Log Handler"
3. Click refresh button (ref from snapshot)
4. Wait 2 seconds for data
5. Verify data populated (check snapshot for values)
6. Click theme toggle
7. Verify theme changed (icon changed from 🌙 to ☀️)
8. Check console for JS errors
9. Take screenshot
10. Navigate to next page
```

## Reading Large Snapshots

When snapshots are large, they're saved to files:
```
Snapshot File: C:\Users\FKGEISTA\.cursor\browser-logs\snapshot-*.log
```

Use the Read tool to examine specific line ranges of these files.

## Best Practices

1. **Always check refs**: Element refs change between page loads - always use refs from the most recent snapshot

2. **Wait after clicks**: Dynamic content needs time to load - use `browser_wait_for` after interactions

3. **Verify before proceeding**: Check the snapshot after each interaction to confirm expected changes

4. **Check console errors**: Run `browser_console_messages` periodically to catch JS errors

5. **Document test results**: Create a structured report with PASS/FAIL status for each test

6. **Test all interactions**: Don't just verify pages load - test buttons, forms, navigation, modals

## Test Report Format

```
=== CHROME AUTOMATED TEST REPORT ===
Date: YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss

== PAGE LOAD TESTS ==
[PASS/FAIL] Page Name - Description

== INTERACTIVE TESTS ==
[PASS/FAIL] Feature - Action tested

== DATA VERIFICATION ==
[PASS/FAIL] Data type - Expected vs Actual

== CONSOLE ERRORS ==
[PASS/FAIL] Error count or "No errors"

== SUMMARY ==
Total Tests: N
Passed: N
Failed: N
Success Rate: N%
```

## DedgeAuth SSO Note

When testing pages with DedgeAuth authentication, the browser extension handles the login redirect automatically if a valid session exists. If not authenticated, the user is redirected to the DedgeAuth login page. The DedgeAuth user menu (`#DedgeAuthUserMenu`) will show authentication status when the user is logged in.

## Limitations

- MCP browser runs in a separate context - some localhost services may need special handling
- Screenshots are saved to temp directory
- Large pages may have truncated snapshots (check the saved file)
- Real-time updates (WebSocket/SSE) may need explicit waits
